article.description: Vicky Bullett made two free throws with 22 seconds to play to give the Washington Mystics a 64-63 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Minnesota native Miller leads Mystics with 22 points
article.linkText: Without Holdsclaw, Mystics win second straight by one point
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Vicky Bullett made two free throws with 22 seconds to play to give the Washington Mystics a 64-63 victory over the Minnesota Lynx on Wednesday night. Svetlana Abrosimova's shot at the buzzer missed off the glass and Washington had its second straight one-point win. Guard Coco Miller, a native of Minnesota, scored a career-high 22 points for the Mystics (12-4), who were playing without injured star Chamique Holdsclaw. "It's always fun to be back home,'' said Miller, who had 10 family members and more than 20 friends in attendance. "They played a physical game and took it to us, but I was happy that we could hang in there for the win.'' Despite playing much of the second half in foul trouble, Miller scored 13 points in the final 20 minutes. She was 7-of-12 from the field and had six rebounds and four assists. "She put a lot of time into her game in the off season and it shows,'' Lynx coach Brian Agler said of Miller. "She hit some big shots tonight and that's typical because she always plays so hard, and with constant motion.'' Katie Smith paced Minnesota with 18 points, while Shaunzinski Gortman added 11 on 5-of-7 shooting for the Lynx (6-9), who saw their two-game winning streak end. Smith made two free throws with 30 seconds left to give the Lynx their last lead, 63-62. Washington scored the game's first six points before Minnesota responded with a 14-3 run and relinquished the lead only briefly in the first half. The Mystics hit four 3-point shots in the first half, but trailed 35-33 at halftime as Smith had 14 points. "They got some easy transition baskets when we weren't pressing,'' Washington coach Marianne Stanley said. "Once we got some more consistent pressure, we were able to get back in the game.'' Bullett led Washington with seven rebounds, while Tamara Moore led Minnesota with the same number.

Game notes
Holdsclaw, who is on the injured list with a sprained left ankle, is the Eastern Conference's leading vote-getter in All-Star game balloting with 42,022 votes. She trails only Sheryl Swoopes of the Houston Comets, who has 43,786. The All-Star game will be played in Washington on July 15. ... Minnesota forward Tamika Williams left the game and did not return after a first-half collision during which she suffered a laceration inside her mouth. The cut required 15 stitches. ... With Wednesday's win, the two teams remained perfect in the other's building. The Mystics are 3-0 all-time at Target Center, while the Lynx are 3-0 at the MCI Center.
